| Entity | Max UDFs |
|--------|----------|
| Companies | 200 |
| Contacts | 100 |
| Contracts | 50 |
| ConfigurationItems | 500 |
| Opportunities | 200 |
| Products | 100 |
| Projects | 200 |
| SalesOrders | 100 |
| Services | 100 |
| ServiceBundles | 100 |
| Subscriptions | 100 |
| Tasks | 100 |
| Tickets | 300 |
| CompanySiteConfigurations | 500 |

### UDF Data Types and Operators

| Type | Supported Operators |
|------|---------------------|
| String | eq, noteq, beginsWith, endsWith, contains |
| Number | eq, noteq, gt, gte, lt, lte |
| Date | eq, noteq, gt, gte, lt, lte |
| List | eq, noteq, in, notIn |
| Boolean | eq |

### UDF Response Format

UDF values appear in `userDefinedFields` array on entity responses:

```json
{
  "id": 12345,
  "companyName": "ACME Corp",
  "userDefinedFields": [
    {"name": "CustomerRanking", "value": "Golden"},
    {"name": "ContractRenewalDate", "value": "2024-06-01"}
  ]
}
```

### UDF Best Practices

- Use UDFs for integration data, not External fields
- Max 5 unique UDFs per query (C# entities)
- Cannot delete UDFs via API
- Cannot query multi-select or reference UDFs
- Protected UDF queries are case-sensitive
- Use `exist`/`notExist` for null checks

